<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06289099 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06289099 </ACCESS><CAPTION>  Photo; PHOTO: (rodeo)  </CAPTION><DESCRIPT>  ENTERTAINMENT; BRIEF  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  Ride 'em, cowpersons.;   Rodeo is one of the nation's oldest sports, and it'sbecoming one of its more popular. The number of rodeos has increased by 25percent in the last four years, to over 800. The prizes at the National RodeoFinals add up to more than $2.5 million. And, says the New York Times, it's agrowing attraction on cable TV.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Living  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  TIME TO SADDLE UP  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  What's Hot  </MEMO><TEXT>     OK, so maybe you don't want to trust rodeo information you get from the NewYork Times. But you can't make a late-night run through the channels withoutseeing some cowpoke bouncing on a bronco. And gay rodeos and black rodeos arewinning the sport new fans.;   Except among animal-rights advocates. Theythink the whole thing's a bum steer.; GETTING OUT; (box) TONIGHT: &quot;MajorBarbara&quot; and &quot;Pygmalion&quot; trade Shavian quips at the Stanford Theatre, 221University Ave., Palo Alto. (415) 324-3700.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  -- Stephen Whitty  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   911015  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Tuesday  </DAY><MONTH>  October  </MONTH><PG.COL>  3C  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><FEATURE>  PHOTO  </FEATURE><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  152  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Tuesday, October 15, 199100289099,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>